result.execSummary:
The defendant Robert D Hensler was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse, Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. 10:31 a.m.   State by DA Andrew Christenson.  Defendant present, in custody, with Attorney Jon Wilsnack.

Court reads agreement - defendant to plea to misdemeanor Disorderly Conduct (with domestic abuse) and misdemeanor Bail Jumping.  DA concurs.  Attorney Wilsnack concurs.  Defendant concurs.  DA moves to dismiss the repeater on both counts.

Court goes over plea questionnaire with the defendant.  Court goes over constitutional rights with the defendant - waived.  Court goes over the elements for each offense.  Court instructs regarding the maximum penalties.  Court instructs regarding deportation.  Counsel indicate count 1 will be dismissed and readin.  

Defendant enters a plea of NO CONTEST to counts 2 and 3.  Court finds the pleas are made freely, voluntarily, intelligently, and understandingly.  Court finds there is a factual basis to support each plea.  Court finds the defendant guilty on counts 2 (DC - domestic abuse) and 3 (bail jumping) and orders a judgment of conviction be entered today.  Court strikes the repeaters (counts 2 and 3) and the domestic abuse repeater on count 2.  DA confirms compliance with any victim/witness rights.  Sentencing argument by Attorney Wilsnack.  No statement by the defendant.

Count 2
Pay court costs and pay $100.00 domestic abuse surcharge.

Count 3
Pay court costs.
Court sentences the defendant to "time served."

Court grants sixty days to pay or payment plan.  Court orders that If the defendant is sentenced to prison, court authorizes 25% of earnings be applied towards the costs.
